45Rm 1:1 Paul, a slave of Christ Jesus, called as an apostle and singled out for God's good news--
45Rm 1:2 which He promised long ago through His prophets in the Holy Scriptures--
45Rm 1:3 concerning His Son, Jesus Christ our Lord, who was a descendant of David according to the flesh
45Rm 1:4 and was established as the powerful Son of God by the resurrection from the dead according to the Spirit of holiness.
45Rm 1:5 We have received grace and apostleship through Him to bring about the obedience of faith among all the nations, on behalf of His name,
45Rm 1:6 including yourselves who are also Jesus Christ's by calling:
45Rm 1:7 To all who are in Rome, loved by God, called as saints. Grace to you and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
45Rm 1:8 First, I thank my God through Jesus Christ for all of you because the news of your faith is being reported in all the world.
45Rm 1:9 For God, whom I serve with my spirit in [telling] the good news about His Son, is my witness that I constantly mention you,
45Rm 1:10 always asking in my prayers that if it is somehow in God's will, I may now at last succeed in coming to you.
45Rm 1:11 For I want very much to see you, that I may impart to you some spiritual gift to strengthen you,
45Rm 1:12 that is, to be mutually encouraged by each other's faith, both yours and mine.
45Rm 1:13 Now I want you to know, brothers, that I often planned to come to you (but was prevented until now) in order that I might have a fruitful ministry among you, just as among the rest of the Gentiles.
45Rm 1:14 I am obligated both to Greeks and barbarians, both to the wise and the foolish.
45Rm 1:15 So I am eager to preach the good news to you also who are in Rome.
45Rm 1:16 For I am not ashamed of the gospel, because it is God's power for salvation to everyone who believes, first to the Jew, and also to the Greek.
45Rm 1:17 For in it God's righteousness is revealed from faith to faith, just as it is written: The righteous will live by faith.
45Rm 1:18 For God's wrath is revealed from heaven against all godlessness and unrighteousness of people who by their unrighteousness suppress the truth,
45Rm 1:19 since what can be known about God is evident among them, because God has shown it to them.
45Rm 1:20 From the creation of the world His invisible attributes, that is, His eternal power and divine nature, have been clearly seen, being understood through what He has made. As a result, people are without excuse.
45Rm 1:21 For though they knew God, they did not glorify Him as God or show gratitude. Instead, their thinking became nonsense, and their senseless minds were darkened.
45Rm 1:22 Claiming to be wise, they became fools
45Rm 1:23 and exchanged the glory of the immortal God for images resembling mortal man, birds, four-footed animals, and reptiles.
45Rm 1:24 Therefore God delivered them over in the cravings of their hearts to sexual impurity, so that their bodies were degraded among themselves.
45Rm 1:25 They exchanged the truth of God for a lie, and worshiped and served something created instead of the Creator, who is blessed forever. Amen.
45Rm 1:26 This is why God delivered them over to degrading passions. For even their females exchanged natural sexual intercourse for what is unnatural.
45Rm 1:27 The males in the same way also left natural sexual intercourse with females and were inflamed in their lust for one another. Males committed shameless acts with males and received in their own persons the appropriate penalty for their perversion.
45Rm 1:28 And because they did not think it worthwhile to have God in their knowledge, God delivered them over to a worthless mind to do what is morally wrong.
45Rm 1:29 They are filled with all unrighteousness, evil, greed, and wickedness. They are full of envy, murder, disputes, deceit, and malice. They are gossips,
45Rm 1:30 slanderers, God-haters, arrogant, proud, boastful, inventors of evil, disobedient to parents,
45Rm 1:31 undiscerning, untrustworthy, unloving, and unmerciful.
45Rm 1:32 Although they know full well God's just sentence-- that those who practice such things deserve to die-- they not only do them, but even applaud others who practice them.
45Rm 2:1 Therefore, anyone of you who judges is without excuse. For when you judge another, you condemn yourself, since you, the judge, do the same things.
45Rm 2:2 We know that God's judgment on those who do such things is based on the truth.
45Rm 2:3 Do you really think-- anyone of you who judges those who do such things yet do the same-- that you will escape God's judgment?
45Rm 2:4 Or do you despise the riches of His kindness, restraint, and patience, not recognizing that God's kindness is intended to lead you to repentance?
45Rm 2:5 But because of your hardness and unrepentant heart you are storing up wrath for yourself in the day of wrath, when God's righteous judgment is revealed.
45Rm 2:6 He will repay each one according to his works:
45Rm 2:7 eternal life to those who by patiently doing good seek for glory, honor, and immortality;
45Rm 2:8 but wrath and indignation to those who are self-seeking and disobey the truth, but are obeying unrighteousness;
45Rm 2:9 affliction and distress for every human being who does evil, first to the Jew, and also to the Greek;
45Rm 2:10 but glory, honor, and peace for everyone who does good, first to the Jew, and also to the Greek.
45Rm 2:11 There is no favoritism with God.
45Rm 2:12 All those who sinned without the law will also perish without the law, and all those who sinned under the law will be judged by the law.
45Rm 2:13 For the hearers of the law are not righteous before God, but the doers of the law will be declared righteous.
45Rm 2:14 So, when Gentiles, who do not have the law, instinctively do what the law demands, they are a law to themselves even though they do not have the law.
45Rm 2:15 They show that the work of the law is written on their hearts. Their consciences testify in support of this, and their competing thoughts either accuse or excuse them
45Rm 2:16 on the day when God judges what people have kept secret, according to my gospel through Christ Jesus.
45Rm 2:17 Now if you call yourself a Jew, and rest in the law, and boast in God,
45Rm 2:18 and know His will, and approve the things that are superior, being instructed from the law,
45Rm 2:19 and are convinced that you are a guide for the blind, a light to those in darkness,
45Rm 2:20 an instructor of the ignorant, a teacher of the immature, having in the law the full expression of knowledge and truth--
45Rm 2:21 you then, who teach another, do you not teach yourself? You who preach, "You must not steal"-- do you steal?
45Rm 2:22 You who say, "You must not commit adultery"-- do you commit adultery? You who detest idols, do you rob their temples?
45Rm 2:23 You who boast in the law, do you dishonor God by breaking the law?
45Rm 2:24 For, as it is written: The name of God is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you.
45Rm 2:25 For circumcision benefits you if you observe the law, but if you are a lawbreaker, your circumcision has become uncircumcision.
45Rm 2:26 Therefore if an uncircumcised man keeps the law's requirements, will his uncircumcision not be counted as circumcision?
45Rm 2:27 A man who is physically uncircumcised, but who fulfills the law, will judge you who are a lawbreaker in spite of having the letter [of the law] and circumcision.
45Rm 2:28 For a person is not a Jew who is one outwardly, and [true] circumcision is not something visible in the flesh.
45Rm 2:29 On the contrary, a person is a Jew who is one inwardly, and circumcision is of the heart-- by the Spirit, not the letter. His praise is not from men but from God.
45Rm 3:1 So what advantage does the Jew have? Or what is the benefit of circumcision?
45Rm 3:2 Considerable in every way. First, they were entrusted with the spoken words of God.
45Rm 3:3 What then? If some did not believe, will their unbelief cancel God's faithfulness?
45Rm 3:4 Absolutely not! God must be true, but everyone is a liar, as it is written: That You may be justified in Your words and triumph when You judge.
45Rm 3:5 But if our unrighteousness highlights God's righteousness, what are we to say? I use a human argument: Is God unrighteous to inflict wrath?
45Rm 3:6 Absolutely not! Otherwise, how will God judge the world?
45Rm 3:7 But if by my lie God's truth is amplified to His glory, why am I also still judged as a sinner?
45Rm 3:8 And why not say, just as some people slanderously claim we say, "Let us do evil so that good may come"? Their condemnation is deserved!
45Rm 3:9 What then? Are we any better? Not at all! For we have previously charged that both Jews and Gentiles are all under sin,
45Rm 3:10 as it is written: There is no one righteous, not even one;
45Rm 3:11 there is no one who understands, there is no one who seeks God.
45Rm 3:12 All have turned away, together they have become useless; there is no one who does good, there is not even one.
45Rm 3:13 Their throat is an open grave; they deceive with their tongues. Vipers' venom is under their lips.
45Rm 3:14 Their mouth is full of cursing and bitterness.
45Rm 3:15 Their feet are swift to shed blood;
45Rm 3:16 ruin and wretchedness are in their paths,
45Rm 3:17 and the path of peace they have not known.
45Rm 3:18 There is no fear of God before their eyes.
45Rm 3:19 Now we know that whatever the law says speaks to those who are subject to the law, so that every mouth may be shut and the whole world may become subject to God's judgment.
45Rm 3:20 For no flesh will be justified in His sight by the works of the law, for through the law [comes] the knowledge of sin.
45Rm 3:21 But now, apart from the law, God's righteousness has been revealed-- attested by the Law and the Prophets
45Rm 3:22 -- that is, God's righteousness through faith in Jesus Christ, to all who believe, since there is no distinction.
45Rm 3:23 For all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God.
45Rm 3:24 They are justified freely by His grace through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus.
45Rm 3:25 God presented Him as a propitiation through faith in His blood, to demonstrate His righteousness, because in His restraint God passed over the sins previously committed.
45Rm 3:26 He presented Him to demonstrate His righteousness at the present time, so that He would be righteous and declare righteous the one who has faith in Jesus.
45Rm 3:27 Where then is boasting? It is excluded. By what kind of law? By one of works? No, on the contrary, by a law of faith.
45Rm 3:28 For we conclude that a man is justified by faith apart from works of law.
45Rm 3:29 Or is God for Jews only? Is He not also for Gentiles? Yes, for Gentiles too,
45Rm 3:30 since there is one God who will justify the circumcised by faith and the uncircumcised through faith.
45Rm 3:31 Do we then cancel the law through faith? Absolutely not! On the contrary, we uphold the law.
45Rm 4:1 What then can we say that Abraham, our forefather according to the flesh, has found?
45Rm 4:2 If Abraham was justified by works, then he has something to brag about-- but not before God.
45Rm 4:3 For what does the Scripture say? Abraham believed God, and it was credited to him for righteousness.
45Rm 4:4 Now to the one who works, pay is not considered as a gift, but as something owed.
45Rm 4:5 But to the one who does not work, but believes on Him who declares righteous the ungodly, his faith is credited for righteousness.
45Rm 4:6 Likewise, David also speaks of the blessing of the man to whom God credits righteousness apart from works:
45Rm 4:7 How happy those whose lawless acts are forgiven and whose sins are covered!
45Rm 4:8 How happy the man whom the Lord will never charge with sin!
45Rm 4:9 Is this blessing only for the circumcised, then? Or is it also for the uncircumcised? For we say, Faith was credited to Abraham for righteousness.
45Rm 4:10 How then was it credited-- while he was circumcised, or uncircumcised? Not while he was circumcised, but uncircumcised.
45Rm 4:11 And he received the sign of circumcision as a seal of the righteousness that he had by faith while still uncircumcised. This was to make him the father of all who believe but are not circumcised, so that righteousness may be credited to them also.
45Rm 4:12 And he became the father of the circumcised, not only to those who are circumcised, but also to those who follow in the footsteps of the faith our father Abraham had while still uncircumcised.
45Rm 4:13 For the promise to Abraham or to his descendants that he would inherit the world was not through the law, but through the righteousness that comes by faith.
45Rm 4:14 If those who are of the law are heirs, faith is made empty and the promise is canceled.
45Rm 4:15 For the law produces wrath; but where there is no law, there is no transgression.
45Rm 4:16 This is why the promise is by faith, so that it may be according to grace, to guarantee it to all the descendants-- not only to those who are of the law, but also to those who are of Abraham's faith. He is the father of us all
45Rm 4:17 in God's sight. As it is written: I have made you the father of many nations. He believed in God, who gives life to the dead and calls things into existence that do not exist.
45Rm 4:18 Against hope, with hope he believed, so that he became the father of many nations, according to what had been spoken: So will your descendants be.
45Rm 4:19 He considered his own body to be already dead (since he was about a hundred years old), and the deadness of Sarah's womb, without weakening in the faith.
45Rm 4:20 He did not waver in unbelief at God's promise, but was strengthened in his faith and gave glory to God,
45Rm 4:21 because he was fully convinced that what He had promised He was also able to perform.
45Rm 4:22 Therefore, it was credited to him for righteousness.
45Rm 4:23 Now it was credited to him was not written for Abraham alone,
45Rm 4:24 but also for us. It will be credited to us who believe in Him who raised Jesus our Lord from the dead.
45Rm 4:25 He was delivered up for our trespasses and raised for our justification.
45Rm 5:1 Therefore, since we have been declared righteous by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ.
45Rm 5:2 Also through Him, we have obtained access by faith into this grace in which we stand, and we rejoice in the hope of the glory of God.
45Rm 5:3 And not only that, but we also rejoice in our afflictions, because we know that affliction produces endurance,
45Rm 5:4 endurance produces proven character, and proven character produces hope.
45Rm 5:5 This hope does not disappoint, because God's love has been poured out in our hearts through the Holy Spirit who was given to us.
45Rm 5:6 For while we were still helpless, at the appointed moment, Christ died for the ungodly.
45Rm 5:7 For rarely will someone die for a just person-- though for a good person perhaps someone might even dare to die.
45Rm 5:8 But God proves His own love for us in that while we were still sinners Christ died for us!
45Rm 5:9 Much more then, since we have now been declared righteous by His blood, we will be saved through Him from wrath.
45Rm 5:10 For if, while we were enemies, we were reconciled to God through the death of His Son, [then how] much more, having been reconciled, will we be saved by His life!
45Rm 5:11 And not only that, but we also rejoice in God through our Lord Jesus Christ, through whom we have now received reconciliation.
45Rm 5:12 Therefore, just as sin entered the world through one man, and death through sin, in this way death spread to all men, because all sinned.
45Rm 5:13 In fact, sin was in the world before the law, but sin is not charged to one's account when there is no law.
45Rm 5:14 Nevertheless, death reigned from Adam to Moses, even over those who did not sin in the likeness of Adam's transgression. He is a prototype of the Coming One.
45Rm 5:15 But the gift is not like the trespass. For if by the one man's trespass the many died, how much more have the grace of God and the gift overflowed to the many by the grace of the one man, Jesus Christ.
45Rm 5:16 And the gift is not like the one man's sin, because from one sin came the judgment, resulting in condemnation, but from many trespasses came the gift, resulting in justification.
45Rm 5:17 Since by the one man's trespass, death reigned through that one man, how much more will those who receive the overflow of grace and the gift of righteousness reign in life through the one man, Jesus Christ.
45Rm 5:18 So then, as through one trespass there is condemnation for everyone, so also through one righteous act there is life-giving justification for everyone.
45Rm 5:19 For just as through one man's disobedience the many were made sinners, so also through the one man's obedience the many will be made righteous.
45Rm 5:20 The law came along to multiply the trespass. But where sin multiplied, grace multiplied even more,
45Rm 5:21 so that, just as sin reigned in death, so also grace will reign through righteousness, resulting in eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord.
45Rm 6:1 What should we say then? Should we continue in sin in order that grace may multiply?
45Rm 6:2 Absolutely not! How can we who died to sin still live in it?
45Rm 6:3 Or are you unaware that all of us who were baptized into Christ Jesus were baptized into His death?
45Rm 6:4 Therefore we were buried with Him by baptism into death, in order that, just as Christ was raised from the dead by the glory of the Father, so we too may walk in a new way of life.
45Rm 6:5 For if we have been joined with Him in the likeness of His death, we will certainly also be in the likeness of His resurrection.
45Rm 6:6 For we know that our old self was crucified with Him in order that sin's dominion over the body may be abolished, so that we may no longer be enslaved to sin,
45Rm 6:7 since a person who has died is freed from sin's claims.
45Rm 6:8 Now if we died with Christ, we believe that we will also live with Him,
45Rm 6:9 because we know that Christ, having been raised from the dead, no longer dies. Death no longer rules over Him.
45Rm 6:10 For in that He died, He died to sin once for all; but in that He lives, He lives to God.
45Rm 6:11 So, you too consider yourselves dead to sin, but alive to God in Christ Jesus.
45Rm 6:12 Therefore do not let sin reign in your mortal body, so that you obey its desires.
45Rm 6:13 And do not offer any parts of it to sin as weapons for unrighteousness. But as those who are alive from the dead, offer yourselves to God, and all the parts of yourselves to God as weapons for righteousness.
45Rm 6:14 For sin will not rule over you, because you are not under law but under grace.
45Rm 6:15 What then? Should we sin because we are not under law but under grace? Absolutely not!
45Rm 6:16 Do you not know that if you offer yourselves to someone as obedient slaves, you are slaves of that one you obey-- either of sin leading to death or of obedience leading to righteousness?
45Rm 6:17 But thank God that, although you used to be slaves of sin, you obeyed from the heart that pattern of teaching you were entrusted to,
45Rm 6:18 and having been liberated from sin, you became enslaved to righteousness.
45Rm 6:19 I am using a human analogy because of the weakness of your flesh. For just as you offered the parts of yourselves as slaves to moral impurity, and to greater and greater lawlessness, so now offer them as slaves to righteousness, which results in sanctification.
45Rm 6:20 For when you were slaves of sin, you were free from allegiance to righteousness.
45Rm 6:21 And what fruit was produced then from the things you are now ashamed of? For the end of those things is death.
45Rm 6:22 But now, since you have been liberated from sin and become enslaved to God, you have your fruit, which results in sanctification-- and the end is eternal life!
45Rm 6:23 For the wages of sin is death, but the gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.
45Rm 7:1 Since I am speaking to those who understand law, brothers, are you unaware that the law has authority over someone as long as he lives?
45Rm 7:2 For example, a married woman is legally bound to her husband while he lives. But if her husband dies, she is released from the law regarding the husband.
45Rm 7:3 So then, if she gives herself to another man while her husband is living, she will be called an adulteress. But if her husband dies, she is free from that law. Then, if she gives herself to another man, she is not an adulteress.
45Rm 7:4 Therefore, my brothers, you also were put to death in relation to the law through the [crucified] body of the Messiah, so that you may belong to another-- to Him who was raised from the dead-- that we may bear fruit for God.
45Rm 7:5 For when we were in the flesh, the sinful passions operated through the law in every part of us and bore fruit for death.
45Rm 7:6 But now we have been released from the law, since we have died to what held us, so that we may serve in the new way of the Spirit and not in the old letter of the law.
45Rm 7:7 What should we say then? Is the law sin? Absolutely not! On the contrary, I would not have known sin if it were not for the law. For example, I would not have known what it is to covet if the law had not said, You shall not covet.
45Rm 7:8 And sin, seizing an opportunity through the commandment, produced in me coveting of every kind. For apart from the law sin is dead.
45Rm 7:9 Once I was alive apart from the law, but when the commandment came, sin sprang to life
45Rm 7:10 and I died. The commandment that was meant for life resulted in death for me.
45Rm 7:11 For sin, seizing an opportunity through the commandment, deceived me, and through it killed me.
45Rm 7:12 So then, the law is holy, and the commandment is holy and just and good.
45Rm 7:13 Therefore, did what is good cause my death? Absolutely not! On the contrary, sin, in order to be recognized as sin, was producing death in me through what is good, so that through the commandment sin might become sinful beyond measure.
45Rm 7:14 For we know that the law is spiritual; but I am made out of flesh, sold into sin's power.
45Rm 7:15 For I do not understand what I am doing, because I do not practice what I want to do, but I do what I hate.
45Rm 7:16 And if I do what I do not want to do, I agree with the law that it is good.
45Rm 7:17 So now I am no longer the one doing it, but it is sin living in me.
45Rm 7:18 For I know that nothing good lives in me, that is, in my flesh. For the desire to do what is good is with me, but there is no ability to do it.
45Rm 7:19 For I do not do the good that I want to do, but I practice the evil that I do not want to do.
45Rm 7:20 Now if I do what I do not want, I am no longer the one doing it, but it is the sin that lives in me.
45Rm 7:21 So I discover this principle: when I want to do good, evil is with me.
45Rm 7:22 For in my inner self I joyfully agree with God's law.
45Rm 7:23 But I see a different law in the parts of my body, waging war against the law of my mind and taking me prisoner to the law of sin in the parts of my body.
45Rm 7:24 What a wretched man I am! Who will rescue me from this body of death?
45Rm 7:25 I thank God through Jesus Christ our Lord! So then, with my mind I myself am a slave to the law of God, but with my flesh, to the law of sin.
45Rm 8:1 Therefore, no condemnation now exists for those in Christ Jesus,
45Rm 8:2 because the Spirit's law of life in Christ Jesus has set you free from the law of sin and of death.
45Rm 8:3 What the law could not do since it was limited by the flesh, God did. He condemned sin in the flesh by sending His own Son in flesh like ours under sin's domain, and as a sin offering,
45Rm 8:4 in order that the law's requirement would be accomplished in us who do not walk according to the flesh but according to the Spirit.
45Rm 8:5 For those whose lives are according to the flesh think about the things of the flesh, but those whose lives are according to the Spirit, about the things of the Spirit.
45Rm 8:6 For the mind-set of the flesh is death, but the mind-set of the Spirit is life and peace.
45Rm 8:7 For the mind-set of the flesh is hostile to God because it does not submit itself to God's law, for it is unable to do so.
45Rm 8:8 Those whose lives are in the flesh are unable to please God.
45Rm 8:9 You, however, are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit, since the Spirit of God lives in you. But if anyone does not have the Spirit of Christ, he does not belong to Him.
45Rm 8:10 Now if Christ is in you, the body is dead because of sin, but the Spirit is life because of righteousness.
45Rm 8:11 And if the Spirit of Him who raised Jesus from the dead lives in you, then He who raised Christ from the dead will also bring your mortal bodies to life through His Spirit who lives in you.
45Rm 8:12 So then, brothers, we are not obligated to the flesh to live according to the flesh,
45Rm 8:13 for if you live according to the flesh, you are going to die. But if by the Spirit you put to death the deeds of the body, you will live.
45Rm 8:14 All those led by God's Spirit are God's sons.
45Rm 8:15 For you did not receive a spirit of slavery to fall back into fear, but you received the Spirit of adoption, by whom we cry out, "Abba, Father!"
45Rm 8:16 The Spirit Himself testifies together with our spirit that we are God's children,
45Rm 8:17 and if children, also heirs-- heirs of God and co-heirs with Christ-- seeing that we suffer with Him so that we may also be glorified with Him.
45Rm 8:18 For I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worth comparing with the glory that is going to be revealed to us.
45Rm 8:19 For the creation eagerly waits with anticipation for God's sons to be revealed.
45Rm 8:20 For the creation was subjected to futility-- not willingly, but because of Him who subjected it-- in the hope
45Rm 8:21 that the creation itself will also be set free from the bondage of corruption into the glorious freedom of God's children.
45Rm 8:22 For we know that the whole creation has been groaning together with labor pains until now.
45Rm 8:23 And not only that, but we ourselves who have the Spirit as the firstfruits-- we also groan within ourselves, eagerly waiting for adoption, the redemption of our bodies.
45Rm 8:24 Now in this hope we were saved, yet hope that is seen is not hope, because who hopes for what he sees?
45Rm 8:25 But if we hope for what we do not see, we eagerly wait for it with patience.
45Rm 8:26 In the same way the Spirit also joins to help in our weakness, because we do not know what to pray for as we should, but the Spirit Himself intercedes for us with unspoken groanings.
45Rm 8:27 And He who searches the hearts knows the Spirit's mind-set, because He intercedes for the saints according to the will of God.
45Rm 8:28 We know that all things work together for the good of those who love God: those who are called according to His purpose.
45Rm 8:29 For those He foreknew He also predestined to be conformed to the image of His Son, so that He would be the firstborn among many brothers.
45Rm 8:30 And those He predestined, He also called; and those He called, He also justified; and those He justified, He also glorified.
45Rm 8:31 What then are we to say about these things? If God is for us, who is against us?
45Rm 8:32 He did not even spare His own Son, but offered Him up for us all; how will He not also with Him grant us everything?
45Rm 8:33 Who can bring an accusation against God's elect? God is the One who justifies.
45Rm 8:34 Who is the one who condemns? Christ Jesus is the One who died, but even more, has been raised; He also is at the right hand of God and intercedes for us.
45Rm 8:35 Who can separate us from the love of Christ? Can affliction or anguish or persecution or famine or nakedness or danger or sword?
45Rm 8:36 As it is written: Because of You we are being put to death all day long; we are counted as sheep to be slaughtered.
45Rm 8:37 No, in all these things we are more than victorious through Him who loved us.
45Rm 8:38 For I am persuaded that neither death nor life, nor angels nor rulers, nor things present, nor things to come, nor powers,
45Rm 8:39 nor height, nor depth, nor any other created thing will have the power to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord!
45Rm 9:1 I speak the truth in Christ-- I am not lying; my conscience is testifying to me with the Holy Spirit--
45Rm 9:2 that I have intense sorrow and continual anguish in my heart.
45Rm 9:3 For I could wish that I myself were cursed and cut off from the Messiah for the benefit of my brothers, my countrymen by physical descent.
45Rm 9:4 They are Israelites, and to them belong the adoption, the glory, the covenants, the giving of the law, the temple service, and the promises.
45Rm 9:5 The forefathers are theirs, and from them, by physical descent, came the Messiah, who is God over all, blessed forever. Amen.
45Rm 9:6 But it is not as though the word of God has failed. For not all who are descended from Israel are Israel.
45Rm 9:7 Neither are they all children because they are Abraham's descendants. On the contrary, in Isaac your seed will be called.
45Rm 9:8 That is, it is not the children by physical descent who are God's children, but the children of the promise are considered seed.
45Rm 9:9 For this is the statement of the promise: At this time I will come, and Sarah will have a son.
45Rm 9:10 And not only that, but also when Rebekah became pregnant by Isaac our forefather
45Rm 9:11 (for though they had not been born yet or done anything good or bad, so that God's purpose according to election might stand,
45Rm 9:12 not from works but from the One who calls) she was told: The older will serve the younger.
45Rm 9:13 As it is written: Jacob I have loved, but Esau I have hated.
45Rm 9:14 What should we say then? Is there injustice with God? Absolutely not!
45Rm 9:15 For He tells Moses: I will show mercy to whom I show mercy, and I will have compassion on whom I have compassion.
45Rm 9:16 So then it does not depend on human will or effort, but on God who shows mercy.
45Rm 9:17 For the Scripture tells Pharaoh: For this reason I raised you up: so that I may display My power in you, and that My name may be proclaimed in all the earth.
45Rm 9:18 So then, He shows mercy to whom He wills, and He hardens whom He wills.
45Rm 9:19 You will say to me, therefore, "Why then does He still find fault? For who can resist His will?"
45Rm 9:20 But who are you-- anyone who talks back to God? Will what is formed say to the one who formed it, "Why did you make me like this?"
45Rm 9:21 Or has the potter no right over His clay, to make from the same lump one piece of pottery for honor and another for dishonor?
45Rm 9:22 And what if God, desiring to display His wrath and to make His power known, endured with much patience objects of wrath ready for destruction?
45Rm 9:23 And [what if] He did this to make known the riches of His glory on objects of mercy that He prepared beforehand for glory--
45Rm 9:24 on us whom He also called, not only from the Jews but also from the Gentiles?
45Rm 9:25 As He also says in Hosea: I will call "Not-My-People," "My-People," and she who is "Unloved," "Beloved."
45Rm 9:26 And it will be in the place where they were told, you are not My people, there they will be called sons of the living God.
45Rm 9:27 But Isaiah cries out concerning Israel: Though the number of Israel's sons is like the sand of the sea, only the remnant will be saved;
45Rm 9:28 for the Lord will execute His sentence completely and decisively on the earth.
45Rm 9:29 And just as Isaiah predicted: If the Lord of Hosts had not left us a seed, we would have become like Sodom, and we would have been made like Gomorrah.
45Rm 9:30 What should we say then? Gentiles, who did not pursue righteousness, have obtained righteousness-- namely the righteousness that comes from faith.
45Rm 9:31 But Israel, pursuing the law for righteousness, has not achieved the law.
45Rm 9:32 Why is that? Because they did not pursue it by faith, but as if it were by works. They stumbled over the stumbling stone.
45Rm 9:33 As it is written: Look! I am putting a stone in Zion to stumble over, and a rock to trip over, yet the one who believes on Him will not be put to shame.
45Rm 10:1 Brothers, my heart's desire and prayer to God concerning them is for their salvation!
45Rm 10:2 I can testify about them that they have zeal for God, but not according to knowledge.
45Rm 10:3 Because they disregarded the righteousness from God and attempted to establish their own righteousness, they have not submitted to God's righteousness.
45Rm 10:4 For Christ is the end of the law for righteousness to everyone who believes.
45Rm 10:5 For Moses writes about the righteousness that is from the law: The one who does these things will live by them.
45Rm 10:6 But the righteousness that comes from faith speaks like this: Do not say in your heart, "Who will go up to heaven?" that is, to bring Christ down
45Rm 10:7 or, "Who will go down into the abyss?" that is, to bring Christ up from the dead.
45Rm 10:8 On the contrary, what does it say? The message is near you, in your mouth and in your heart. This is the message of faith that we proclaim:
45Rm 10:9 if you confess with your mouth, "Jesus is Lord," and believe in your heart that God raised Him from the dead, you will be saved.
45Rm 10:10 With the heart one believes, resulting in righteousness, and with the mouth one confesses, resulting in salvation.
45Rm 10:11 Now the Scripture says, No one who believes on Him will be put to shame,
45Rm 10:12 for there is no distinction between Jew and Greek, since the same Lord of all is rich to all who call on Him.
45Rm 10:13 For everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved.
45Rm 10:14 But how can they call on Him in whom they have not believed? And how can they believe without hearing about Him? And how can they hear without a preacher?
45Rm 10:15 And how can they preach unless they are sent? As it is written: How welcome are the feet of those who announce the gospel of good things!
45Rm 10:16 But all did not obey the gospel. For Isaiah says, Lord, who has believed our message?
45Rm 10:17 So faith comes from what is heard, and what is heard comes through the message about Christ.
45Rm 10:18 But I ask, "Did they not hear?" Yes, they did: Their voice has gone out to all the earth, and their words to the ends of the inhabited world.
45Rm 10:19 But I ask, "Did Israel not understand?" First, Moses said: I will make you jealous of those who are not a nation; I will make you angry by a nation that lacks understanding.
45Rm 10:20 And Isaiah says boldly: I was found by those who were not looking for Me; I revealed Myself to those who were not asking for Me.
45Rm 10:21 But to Israel he says: All day long I have spread out My hands to a disobedient and defiant people.
45Rm 11:1 I ask, then, has God rejected His people? Absolutely not! For I too am an Israelite, a descendant of Abraham, from the tribe of Benjamin.
45Rm 11:2 God has not rejected His people whom He foreknew. Or do you not know what the Scripture says in the Elijah section-- how he pleads with God against Israel?
45Rm 11:3 Lord, they have killed Your prophets, torn down Your altars; and I am the only one left, and they are trying to take my life!
45Rm 11:4 But what was God's reply to him? I have left 7,000 men for Myself who have not bowed down to Baal.
45Rm 11:5 In the same way, then, there is also at the present time a remnant chosen by grace.
45Rm 11:6 Now if by grace, then it is not by works; otherwise grace ceases to be grace.
45Rm 11:7 What then? Israel did not find what it was looking for, but the elect did find it. The rest were hardened,
45Rm 11:8 as it is written: God gave them a spirit of stupor, eyes that cannot see and ears that cannot hear, to this day.
45Rm 11:9 And David says: Let their feasting become a snare and a trap, a pitfall and a retribution to them.
45Rm 11:10 Let their eyes be darkened so they cannot see, and their backs be bent continually.
45Rm 11:11 I ask, then, have they stumbled so as to fall? Absolutely not! On the contrary, by their stumbling, salvation has come to the Gentiles to make Israel jealous.
45Rm 11:12 Now if their stumbling brings riches for the world, and their failure riches for the Gentiles, how much more will their full number bring!
45Rm 11:13 Now I am speaking to you Gentiles. In view of the fact that I am an apostle to the Gentiles, I magnify my ministry,
45Rm 11:14 if I can somehow make my own people jealous and save some of them.
45Rm 11:15 For if their being rejected is world reconciliation, what will their acceptance mean but life from the dead?
45Rm 11:16 Now if the firstfruits offered up are holy, so is the whole batch. And if the root is holy, so are the branches.
45Rm 11:17 Now if some of the branches were broken off, and you, though a wild olive branch, were grafted in among them, and have come to share in the rich root of the cultivated olive tree,
45Rm 11:18 do not brag that you are better than those branches. But if you do brag-- you do not sustain the root, but the root sustains you.
45Rm 11:19 Then you will say, "Branches were broken off so that I might be grafted in."
45Rm 11:20 True enough; they were broken off by unbelief, but you stand by faith. Do not be arrogant, but be afraid.
45Rm 11:21 For if God did not spare the natural branches, He will not spare you either.
45Rm 11:22 Therefore, consider God's kindness and severity: severity toward those who have fallen, but God's kindness toward you-- if you remain in His kindness. Otherwise you too will be cut off.
45Rm 11:23 And even they, if they do not remain in unbelief, will be grafted in, because God has the power to graft them in again.
45Rm 11:24 For if you were cut off from your native wild olive, and against nature were grafted into a cultivated olive tree, how much more will these-- the natural branches-- be grafted into their own olive tree?
45Rm 11:25 So that you will not be conceited, brothers, I do not want you to be unaware of this mystery: a partial hardening has come to Israel until the full number of the Gentiles has come in.
45Rm 11:26 And in this way all Israel will be saved, as it is written: The Liberator will come from Zion; He will turn away godlessness from Jacob.
45Rm 11:27 And this will be My covenant with them, when I take away their sins.
45Rm 11:28 Regarding the gospel, they are enemies for your advantage, but regarding election, they are loved because of their forefathers,
45Rm 11:29 since God's gracious gifts and calling are irrevocable.
45Rm 11:30 As you once disobeyed God, but now have received mercy through their disobedience,
45Rm 11:31 so they too have now disobeyed, [resulting] in mercy to you, so that they also now may receive mercy.
45Rm 11:32 For God has imprisoned all in disobedience, so that He may have mercy on all.
45Rm 11:33 Oh, the depth of the riches both of the wisdom and the knowledge of God! How unsearchable His judgments and untraceable His ways!
45Rm 11:34 For who has known the mind of the Lord? Or who has been His counselor?
45Rm 11:35 Or who has ever first given to Him, and has to be repaid?
45Rm 11:36 For from Him and through Him and to Him are all things. To Him be the glory forever. Amen.
45Rm 12:1 Therefore, brothers, by the mercies of God, I urge you to present your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God; this is your spiritual worship.
45Rm 12:2 Do not be conformed to this age, but be transformed by the renewing of your mind, so that you may discern what is the good, pleasing, and perfect will of God.
45Rm 12:3 For by the grace given to me, I tell everyone among you not to think of himself more highly than he should think. Instead, think sensibly, as God has distributed a measure of faith to each one.
45Rm 12:4 Now as we have many parts in one body, and all the parts do not have the same function,
45Rm 12:5 in the same way we who are many are one body in Christ and individually members of one another.
45Rm 12:6 According to the grace given to us, we have different gifts: If prophecy, use it according to the standard of faith;
45Rm 12:7 if service, in service; if teaching, in teaching;
45Rm 12:8 if exhorting, in exhortation; giving, with generosity; leading, with diligence; showing mercy, with cheerfulness.
45Rm 12:9 Love must be without hypocrisy. Detest evil; cling to what is good.
45Rm 12:10 Show family affection to one another with brotherly love. Outdo one another in showing honor.
45Rm 12:11 Do not lack diligence; be fervent in spirit; serve the Lord.
45Rm 12:12 Rejoice in hope; be patient in affliction; be persistent in prayer.
45Rm 12:13 Share with the saints in their needs; pursue hospitality.
45Rm 12:14 Bless those who persecute you; bless and do not curse.
45Rm 12:15 Rejoice with those who rejoice; weep with those who weep.
45Rm 12:16 Be in agreement with one another. Do not be proud; instead, associate with the humble. Do not be wise in your own estimation.
45Rm 12:17 Do not repay anyone evil for evil. Try to do what is honorable in everyone's eyes.
45Rm 12:18 If possible, on your part, live at peace with everyone.
45Rm 12:19 Friends, do not avenge yourselves; instead, leave room for His wrath. For it is written: Vengeance belongs to Me; I will repay, says the Lord.
45Rm 12:20 But If your enemy is hungry, feed him. If he is thirsty, give him something to drink. For in so doing you will be heaping fiery coals on his head.
45Rm 12:21 Do not be conquered by evil, but conquer evil with good.
45Rm 13:1 Everyone must submit to the governing authorities, for there is no authority except from God, and those that exist are instituted by God.
45Rm 13:2 So then, the one who resists the authority is opposing God's command, and those who oppose it will bring judgment on themselves.
45Rm 13:3 For rulers are not a terror to good conduct, but to bad. Do you want to be unafraid of the authority? Do good and you will have its approval.
45Rm 13:4 For government is God's servant to you for good. But if you do wrong, be afraid, because it does not carry the sword for no reason. For government is God's servant, an avenger that brings wrath on the one who does wrong.
45Rm 13:5 Therefore, you must submit, not only because of wrath, but also because of your conscience.
45Rm 13:6 And for this reason you pay taxes, since the [authorities] are God's public servants, continually attending to these tasks.
45Rm 13:7 Pay your obligations to everyone: taxes to those you owe taxes, tolls to those you owe tolls, respect to those you owe respect, and honor to those you owe honor.
45Rm 13:8 Do not owe anyone anything, except to love one another, for the one who loves another has fulfilled the law.
45Rm 13:9 The commandments: You shall not commit adultery, you shall not murder, you shall not steal, you shall not covet, and if there is any other commandment-- all are summed up by this: You shall love your neighbor as yourself.
45Rm 13:10 Love does no wrong to a neighbor. Love, therefore, is the fulfillment of the law.
45Rm 13:11 Besides this, knowing the time, it is already the hour for you to wake up from sleep, for now our salvation is nearer than when we first believed.
45Rm 13:12 The night is nearly over, and the daylight is near, so let us discard the deeds of darkness and put on the armor of light.
45Rm 13:13 Let us walk with decency, as in the daylight: not in carousing and drunkenness; not in sexual impurity and promiscuity; not in quarreling and jealousy.
45Rm 13:14 But put on the Lord Jesus Christ, and make no plans to satisfy the fleshly desires.
45Rm 14:1 Accept anyone who is weak in faith, but don't argue about doubtful issues.
45Rm 14:2 One person believes he may eat anything, but one who is weak eats only vegetables.
45Rm 14:3 One who eats must not look down on one who does not eat; and one who does not eat must not criticize one who does, because God has accepted him.
45Rm 14:4 Who are you to criticize another's household slave? Before his own Lord he stands or falls. And stand he will! For the Lord is able to make him stand.
45Rm 14:5 One person considers one day to be above another day. Someone else considers every day to be the same. Each one must be fully convinced in his own mind.
45Rm 14:6 Whoever observes the day, observes it to the Lord. Whoever eats, eats to the Lord, since he gives thanks to God; and whoever does not eat, it is to the Lord that he does not eat, yet he thanks God.
45Rm 14:7 For none of us lives to himself, and no one dies to himself.
45Rm 14:8 If we live, we live to the Lord; and if we die, we die to the Lord. Therefore, whether we live or die, we belong to the Lord.
45Rm 14:9 Christ died and came to life for this: that He might rule over both the dead and the living.
45Rm 14:10 But you, why do you criticize your brother? Or you, why do you look down on your brother? For we will all stand before the judgment seat of God.
45Rm 14:11 For it is written: As I live, says the Lord, every knee will bow to Me, and every tongue will give praise to God.
45Rm 14:12 So then, each of us will give an account of himself to God.
45Rm 14:13 Therefore, let us no longer criticize one another, but instead decide not to put a stumbling block or pitfall in your brother's way.
45Rm 14:14 (I know and am persuaded by the Lord Jesus that nothing is unclean in itself. Still, to someone who considers a thing to be unclean, to that one it is unclean.)
45Rm 14:15 For if your brother is hurt by what you eat, you are no longer walking according to love. By what you eat, do not destroy that one for whom Christ died.
45Rm 14:16 Therefore, do not let your good be slandered,
45Rm 14:17 for the kingdom of God is not eating and drinking, but righteousness, peace, and joy in the Holy Spirit.
45Rm 14:18 Whoever serves the Messiah in this way is acceptable to God and approved by men.
45Rm 14:19 So then, we must pursue what promotes peace and what builds up one another.
45Rm 14:20 Do not tear down God's work because of food. Everything is clean, but it is wrong for a man to cause stumbling by what he eats.
45Rm 14:21 It is a noble thing not to eat meat, or drink wine, or do anything that makes your brother stumble.
45Rm 14:22 Do you have faith? Keep it to yourself before God. Blessed is the man who does not condemn himself by what he approves.
45Rm 14:23 But whoever doubts stands condemned if he eats, because his eating is not from faith, and everything that is not from faith is sin.
45Rm 15:1 Now we who are strong have an obligation to bear the weaknesses of those without strength, and not to please ourselves.
45Rm 15:2 Each one of us must please his neighbor for his good, in order to build him up.
45Rm 15:3 For even the Messiah did not please Himself. On the contrary, as it is written, The insults of those who insult You have fallen on Me.
45Rm 15:4 For whatever was written before was written for our instruction, so that through our endurance and through the encouragement of the Scriptures we may have hope.
45Rm 15:5 Now may the God of endurance and encouragement grant you agreement with one another, according to Christ Jesus,
45Rm 15:6 so that you may glorify the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ with a united mind and voice.
45Rm 15:7 Therefore accept one another, just as the Messiah also accepted you, to the glory of God.
45Rm 15:8 Now I say that Christ has become a servant of the circumcised on behalf of the truth of God, to confirm the promises to the fathers,
45Rm 15:9 and so that Gentiles may glorify God for His mercy. As it is written: Therefore I will praise You among the Gentiles, and I will sing psalms to Your name.
45Rm 15:10 Again it says: Rejoice, you Gentiles, with His people!
45Rm 15:11 And again: Praise the Lord, all you Gentiles; all the peoples should praise Him!
45Rm 15:12 And again, Isaiah says: The root of Jesse will appear, the One who rises to rule the Gentiles; in Him the Gentiles will hope.
45Rm 15:13 Now may the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace in believing, so that you may overflow with hope by the power of the Holy Spirit.
45Rm 15:14 Now, my brothers, I myself am convinced about you that you also are full of goodness, filled with all knowledge, and able to instruct one another.
45Rm 15:15 Nevertheless, to remind you, I have written to you more boldly on some points because of the grace given me by God
45Rm 15:16 to be a minister of Christ Jesus to the Gentiles, serving as a priest of God's good news. My purpose is that the offering of the Gentiles may be acceptable, sanctified by the Holy Spirit.
45Rm 15:17 Therefore I have reason to boast in Christ Jesus regarding what pertains to God.
45Rm 15:18 For I would not dare say anything except what Christ has accomplished through me to make the Gentiles obedient by word and deed,
45Rm 15:19 by the power of miraculous signs and wonders, and by the power of God's Spirit. As a result, I have fully proclaimed the good news about the Messiah from Jerusalem all the way around to Illyricum.
45Rm 15:20 So my aim is to evangelize where Christ has not been named, in order that I will not be building on someone else's foundation,
45Rm 15:21 but, as it is written: Those who had no report of Him will see, and those who have not heard will understand.
45Rm 15:22 That is why I have been prevented many times from coming to you.
45Rm 15:23 But now I no longer have any work to do in these provinces, and I have strongly desired for many years to come to you
45Rm 15:24 whenever I travel to Spain. For I do hope to see you when I pass through, and to be sent on my way there by you, once I have first enjoyed your company for a while.
45Rm 15:25 Now, however, I am traveling to Jerusalem to serve the saints;
45Rm 15:26 for Macedonia and Achaia were pleased to make a contribution to the poor among the saints in Jerusalem.
45Rm 15:27 Yes, they were pleased, and they are indebted to them. For if the Gentiles have shared in their spiritual benefits, then they are obligated to minister to Jews in material needs.
45Rm 15:28 So when I have finished this and safely delivered the funds to them, I will go by way of you to Spain.
45Rm 15:29 But I know that when I come to you, I will come in the fullness of the blessing of Christ.
45Rm 15:30 Now I implore you, brothers, through the Lord Jesus Christ and through the love of the Spirit, to agonize together with me in your prayers to God on my behalf:
45Rm 15:31 that I may be rescued from the unbelievers in Judea, that my service for Jerusalem may be acceptable to the saints,
45Rm 15:32 and that, by God's will, I may come to you with joy and be refreshed together with you.
45Rm 15:33 The God of peace be with all of you. Amen.
45Rm 16:1 I commend to you our sister Phoebe, who is a servant of the church in Cenchreae.
45Rm 16:2 So you should welcome her in the Lord in a manner worthy of the saints, and assist her in whatever matter she may require your help. For indeed she has been a benefactor of many-- and of me also.
45Rm 16:3 Give my greetings to Prisca and Aquila, my co-workers in Christ Jesus,
45Rm 16:4 who risked their own necks for my life. Not only do I thank them, but so do all the Gentile churches.
45Rm 16:5 Greet also the church that meets in their home. Greet my dear friend Epaenetus, who is the first convert to Christ from Asia.
45Rm 16:6 Greet Mary, who has worked very hard for you.
45Rm 16:7 Greet Andronicus and Junia, my fellow countrymen and fellow prisoners. They are outstanding among the apostles, and they were also in Christ before me.
45Rm 16:8 Greet Ampliatus, my dear friend in the Lord.
45Rm 16:9 Greet Urbanus, our co-worker in Christ, and my dear friend Stachys.
45Rm 16:10 Greet Apelles, who is approved in Christ. Greet those who belong to the household of Aristobulus.
45Rm 16:11 Greet Herodion, my fellow countryman. Greet those who belong to the household of Narcissus who are in the Lord.
45Rm 16:12 Greet Tryphaena and Tryphosa, who have worked hard in the Lord. Greet my dear friend Persis, who has worked very hard in the Lord.
45Rm 16:13 Greet Rufus, chosen in the Lord; also his mother-- and mine.
45Rm 16:14 Greet Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes, Patrobas, Hermas, and the brothers who are with them.
45Rm 16:15 Greet Philologus and Julia, Nereus and his sister, and Olympas, and all the saints who are with them.
45Rm 16:16 Greet one another with a holy kiss. All the churches of Christ send you greetings.
45Rm 16:17 Now I implore you, brothers, watch out for those who cause dissensions and pitfalls contrary to the doctrine you have learned. Avoid them;
45Rm 16:18 for such people do not serve our Lord Christ but their own appetites, and by smooth talk and flattering words they deceive the hearts of the unsuspecting.
45Rm 16:19 The report of your obedience has reached everyone. Therefore I rejoice over you. But I want you to be wise about what is good, yet innocent about what is evil.
45Rm 16:20 The God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet. The grace of our Lord Jesus be with you.
45Rm 16:21 Timothy, my co-worker, and Lucius, Jason, and Sosipater, my fellow countrymen, greet you.
45Rm 16:22 I Tertius, who penned this epistle in the Lord, greet you.
45Rm 16:23 Gaius, who is host to me and to the whole church, greets you. Erastus, the city treasurer, and our brother Quartus greet you.
45Rm 16:24 [[The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all.]]
45Rm 16:25 Now to Him who has power to strengthen you according to my gospel and the proclamation of Jesus Christ, according to the revelation of the sacred secret kept silent for long ages,
45Rm 16:26 but now revealed and made known through the prophetic Scriptures, according to the command of the eternal God, to advance the obedience of faith among all nations--
45Rm 16:27 to the only wise God, through Jesus Christ-- to Him be the glory forever! Amen.
