58Heb 1:1 Long ago God spoke to the fathers by the prophets at different times and in different ways.
58Heb 1:2 In these last days, He has spoken to us by [His] Son, whom He has appointed heir of all things and through whom He made the universe.
58Heb 1:3 He is the radiance of His glory, the exact expression of His nature, and He sustains all things by His powerful word. After making purification for sins, He sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high.
58Heb 1:4 So He became higher in rank than the angels, just as the name He inherited is superior to theirs.
58Heb 1:5 For to which of the angels did He ever say, You are My Son; today I have become Your Father, or again, I will be His Father, and He will be My Son?
58Heb 1:6 When He again brings His firstborn into the world, He says, And all God's angels must worship Him.
58Heb 1:7 And about the angels He says: He makes His angels winds, and His servants a fiery flame;
58Heb 1:8 but about the Son: Your throne, O God, is forever and ever, and the scepter of Your kingdom is a scepter of justice.
58Heb 1:9 You have loved righteousness and hated lawlessness; this is why God, Your God, has anointed You, rather than Your companions, with the oil of joy.
58Heb 1:10 And: In the beginning, Lord, You established the earth, and the heavens are the works of Your hands;
58Heb 1:11 they will perish, but You remain. They will all wear out like clothing;
58Heb 1:12 You will roll them up like a cloak, and they will be changed like a robe. But You are the same, and Your years will never end.
58Heb 1:13 Now to which of the angels has He ever said: Sit at My right hand until I make Your enemies Your footstool?
58Heb 1:14 Are they not all ministering spirits sent out to serve those who are going to inherit salvation?
58Heb 2:1 We must therefore pay even more attention to what we have heard, so that we will not drift away.
58Heb 2:2 For if the message spoken through angels was legally binding, and every transgression and disobedience received a just punishment,
58Heb 2:3 how will we escape if we neglect such a great salvation? It was first spoken by the Lord and was confirmed to us by those who heard Him.
58Heb 2:4 At the same time, God also testified by signs and wonders, various miracles, and distributions [of gifts] from the Holy Spirit according to His will.
58Heb 2:5 For He has not subjected to angels the world to come that we are talking about.
58Heb 2:6 But one has somewhere testified: What is man, that You remember him, or the son of man, that You care for him?
58Heb 2:7 You made him lower than the angels for a short time; You crowned him with glory and honor
58Heb 2:8 and subjected everything under his feet. For in subjecting everything to him, He left nothing not subject to him. As it is, we do not yet see everything subjected to him.
58Heb 2:9 But we do see Jesus-- made lower than the angels for a short time so that by God's grace He might taste death for everyone-- crowned with glory and honor because of the suffering of death.
58Heb 2:10 For it was fitting, in bringing many sons to glory, that He, for whom and through whom all things exist, should make the source of their salvation perfect through sufferings.
58Heb 2:11 For the One who sanctifies and those who are sanctified all have one Father. That is why He is not ashamed to call them brothers,
58Heb 2:12 saying: I will proclaim Your name to My brothers; I will sing hymns to You in the congregation.
58Heb 2:13 Again, I will trust in Him. And again, Here I am with the children God gave Me.
58Heb 2:14 Now since the children have flesh and blood in common, He also shared in these, so that through His death He might destroy the one holding the power of death-- that is, the Devil--
58Heb 2:15 and free those who were held in slavery all their lives by the fear of death.
58Heb 2:16 For it is clear that He does not reach out to help angels, but to help Abraham's offspring.
58Heb 2:17 Therefore He had to be like His brothers in every way, so that He could become a merciful and faithful high priest in service to God, to make propitiation for the sins of the people.
58Heb 2:18 For since He Himself was tested and has suffered, He is able to help those who are tested.
58Heb 3:1 Therefore, holy brothers and companions in a heavenly calling, consider Jesus, the apostle and high priest of our confession;
58Heb 3:2 He was faithful to the One who appointed Him, just as Moses was in all God's household.
58Heb 3:3 For Jesus is considered worthy of more glory than Moses, just as the builder has more honor than the house.
58Heb 3:4 Now every house is built by someone, but the One who built everything is God.
58Heb 3:5 Moses was faithful as a servant in all God's household, as a testimony to what would be said [in the future].
58Heb 3:6 But Christ was faithful as a Son over His household, whose household we are if we hold on to the courage and the confidence of our hope.
58Heb 3:7 Therefore, as the Holy Spirit says: Today, if you hear His voice,
58Heb 3:8 do not harden your hearts as in the rebellion, on the day of testing in the desert,
58Heb 3:9 where your fathers tested Me, tried [ Me], and saw My works
58Heb 3:10 for 40 years. Therefore I was provoked with this generation and said, "They always go astray in their hearts, and they have not known My ways."
58Heb 3:11 So I swore in My anger, "They will not enter My rest."
58Heb 3:12 Watch out, brothers, so that there won't be in any of you an evil, unbelieving heart that departs from the living God.
58Heb 3:13 But encourage each other daily, while it is still called today, so that none of you is hardened by sin's deception.
58Heb 3:14 For we have become companions of the Messiah if we hold firmly until the end the reality that we had at the start.
58Heb 3:15 As it is said: Today, if you hear His voice, do not harden your hearts as in the rebellion.
58Heb 3:16 For who heard and rebelled? Wasn't it really all who came out of Egypt under Moses?
58Heb 3:17 And with whom was He "provoked for 40 years"? Was it not with those who sinned, whose bodies fell in the desert?
58Heb 3:18 And to whom did He "swear that they would not enter His rest," if not those who disobeyed?
58Heb 3:19 So we see that they were unable to enter because of unbelief.
58Heb 4:1 Therefore, while the promise remains of entering His rest, let us fear so that none of you should miss it.
58Heb 4:2 For we also have received the good news just as they did; but the message they heard did not benefit them, since they were not united with those who heard it in faith
58Heb 4:3 (for we who have believed enter the rest), in keeping with what He has said: So I swore in My anger, they will not enter My rest. And yet His works have been finished since the foundation of the world,
58Heb 4:4 for somewhere He has spoken about the seventh day in this way: And on the seventh day God rested from all His works.
58Heb 4:5 Again, in that passage [He says], They will never enter My rest.
58Heb 4:6 Since it remains for some to enter it, and those who formerly received the good news did not enter because of disobedience,
58Heb 4:7 again, He specifies a certain day-- today-- speaking through David after such a long time, as previously stated: Today if you hear His voice, do not harden your hearts.
58Heb 4:8 For if Joshua had given them rest, He would not have spoken later about another day.
58Heb 4:9 A Sabbath rest remains, therefore, for God's people.
58Heb 4:10 For the person who has entered His rest has rested from his own works, just as God did from His.
58Heb 4:11 Let us then make every effort to enter that rest, so that no one will fall into the same pattern of disobedience.
58Heb 4:12 For the word of God is living and effective and sharper than any two-edged sword, penetrating as far as to divide soul, spirit, joints, and marrow; it is a judge of the ideas and thoughts of the heart.
58Heb 4:13 No creature is hidden from Him, but all things are naked and exposed to the eyes of Him to whom we must give an account.
58Heb 4:14 Therefore since we have a great high priest who has passed through the heavens-- Jesus the Son of God-- let us hold fast to the confession.
58Heb 4:15 For we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses, but One who has been tested in every way as we are, yet without sin.
58Heb 4:16 Therefore let us approach the throne of grace with boldness, so that we may receive mercy and find grace to help us at the proper time.
58Heb 5:1 For every high priest taken from men is appointed in service to God for the people, to offer both gifts and sacrifices for sins.
58Heb 5:2 He is able to deal gently with those who are ignorant and are going astray, since he himself is also subject to weakness.
58Heb 5:3 Because of this, he must make a sin offering for himself as well as for the people.
58Heb 5:4 No one takes this honor on himself; instead, a person is called by God, just as Aaron was.
58Heb 5:5 In the same way, the Messiah did not exalt Himself to become a high priest, but the One who said to Him, You are My Son; today I have become Your Father,
58Heb 5:6 also said in another passage, You are a priest forever in the order of Melchizedek.
58Heb 5:7 During His earthly life, He offered prayers and appeals, with loud cries and tears, to the One who was able to save Him from death, and He was heard because of His reverence.
58Heb 5:8 Though a Son, He learned obedience through what He suffered.
58Heb 5:9 After He was perfected, He became the source of eternal salvation to all who obey Him,
58Heb 5:10 and He was declared by God a high priest "in the order of Melchizedek."
58Heb 5:11 We have a great deal to say about this, and it's difficult to explain, since you have become slow to understand.
58Heb 5:12 For though by this time you ought to be teachers, you need someone to teach you again the basic principles of God's revelation. You need milk, not solid food.
58Heb 5:13 Now everyone who lives on milk is inexperienced with the message about righteousness, because he is an infant.
58Heb 5:14 But solid food is for the mature-- for those whose senses have been trained to distinguish between good and evil.
58Heb 6:1 Therefore, leaving the elementary message about the Messiah, let us go on to maturity, not laying again the foundation of repentance from dead works, faith in God,
58Heb 6:2 teaching about ritual washings, laying on of hands, the resurrection of the dead, and eternal judgment.
58Heb 6:3 And we will do this if God permits.
58Heb 6:4 For it is impossible to renew to repentance those who were once enlightened, who tasted the heavenly gift, became companions with the Holy Spirit,
58Heb 6:5 tasted God's good word and the powers of the coming age,
58Heb 6:6 and who have fallen away, because, to their own harm, they are recrucifying the Son of God and holding Him up to contempt.
58Heb 6:7 For ground that has drunk the rain that has often fallen on it, and that produces vegetation useful to those it is cultivated for, receives a blessing from God.
58Heb 6:8 But if it produces thorns and thistles, it is worthless and about to be cursed, and will be burned at the end.
58Heb 6:9 Even though we are speaking this way, dear friends, in your case we are confident of the better things connected with salvation.
58Heb 6:10 For God is not unjust; He will not forget your work and the love you showed for His name when you served the saints-- and you continue to serve them.
58Heb 6:11 Now we want each of you to demonstrate the same diligence for the final realization of your hope,
58Heb 6:12 so that you won't become lazy, but imitators of those who inherit the promises through faith and perseverance.
58Heb 6:13 For when God made a promise to Abraham, since He had no one greater to swear by, He swore by Himself:
58Heb 6:14 I will most certainly bless you, and I will greatly multiply you.
58Heb 6:15 And so, after waiting patiently, Abraham obtained the promise.
58Heb 6:16 For men swear by something greater than themselves, and for them a confirming oath ends every dispute.
58Heb 6:17 Because God wanted to show His unchangeable purpose even more clearly to the heirs of the promise, He guaranteed it with an oath,
58Heb 6:18 so that through two unchangeable things, in which it is impossible for God to lie, we who have fled for refuge might have strong encouragement to seize the hope set before us.
58Heb 6:19 We have this [hope]-- like a sure and firm anchor of the soul-- that enters the inner sanctuary behind the curtain.
58Heb 6:20 Jesus has entered there on our behalf as a forerunner, because He has become a "high priest forever in the order of Melchizedek."
58Heb 7:1 For this Melchizedek-- King of Salem, priest of the Most High God, who met Abraham and blessed him as he returned from defeating the kings,
58Heb 7:2 and Abraham gave him a tenth of everything; first, his name means "king of righteousness," then also, "king of Salem," meaning "king of peace";
58Heb 7:3 without father, mother, or genealogy, having neither beginning of days nor end of life, but resembling the Son of God-- remains a priest forever.
58Heb 7:4 Now consider how great this man was, to whom even Abraham the patriarch gave a tenth of the plunder!
58Heb 7:5 The sons of Levi who receive the priestly office have a commandment according to the law to collect a tenth from the people-- that is, from their brothers-- though they have [also] descended from Abraham.
58Heb 7:6 But one without this lineage collected tithes from Abraham and blessed the one who had the promises.
58Heb 7:7 Without a doubt, the inferior is blessed by the superior.
58Heb 7:8 In the one case, men who will die receive tithes; but in the other case, [Scripture] testifies that he lives.
58Heb 7:9 And in a sense Levi himself, who receives tithes, has paid tithes through Abraham,
58Heb 7:10 for he was still within his forefather when Melchizedek met him.
58Heb 7:11 If, then, perfection came through the Levitical priesthood (for under it the people received the law), what further need was there for another priest to arise in the order of Melchizedek, and not to be described as being in the order of Aaron?
58Heb 7:12 For when there is a change of the priesthood, there must be a change of law as well.
58Heb 7:13 For the One about whom these things are said belonged to a different tribe, from which no one has served at the altar.
58Heb 7:14 Now it is evident that our Lord came from Judah, and about that tribe Moses said nothing concerning priests.
58Heb 7:15 And this becomes clearer if another priest like Melchizedek arises,
58Heb 7:16 who doesn't become a [priest] based on a legal command concerning physical descent but based on the power of an indestructible life.
58Heb 7:17 For it has been testified: You are a priest forever in the order of Melchizedek.
58Heb 7:18 So the previous commandment is annulled because it was weak and unprofitable
58Heb 7:19 (for the law perfected nothing), but a better hope is introduced, through which we draw near to God.
58Heb 7:20 None of this [happened] without an oath. For others became priests without an oath,
58Heb 7:21 but He with an oath made by the One who said to Him: The Lord has sworn, and He will not change His mind, You are a priest forever.
58Heb 7:22 So Jesus has also become the guarantee of a better covenant.
58Heb 7:23 Now many have become [Levitical] priests, since they are prevented by death from remaining in office.
58Heb 7:24 But because He remains forever, He holds His priesthood permanently.
58Heb 7:25 Therefore He is always able to save those who come to God through Him, since He always lives to intercede for them.
58Heb 7:26 For this is the kind of high priest we need: holy, innocent, undefiled, separated from sinners, and exalted above the heavens.
58Heb 7:27 He doesn't need to offer sacrifices every day, as high priests do-- first for their own sins, then for those of the people. He did this once for all when He offered Himself.
58Heb 7:28 For the law appoints as high priests men who are weak, but the promise of the oath, which came after the law, [appoints] a Son, who has been perfected forever.
58Heb 8:1 Now the main point of what is being said is this: we have this kind of high priest, who sat down at the right hand of the throne of the Majesty in the heavens,
58Heb 8:2 a minister of the sanctuary and the true tabernacle, which the Lord set up, and not man.
58Heb 8:3 For every high priest is appointed to offer gifts and sacrifices; therefore it was necessary for this [priest] also to have something to offer.
58Heb 8:4 Now if He were on earth, He wouldn't be a priest, since there are those offering the gifts prescribed by the law.
58Heb 8:5 These serve as a copy and shadow of the heavenly things, as Moses was warned when he was about to complete the tabernacle. For He said, Be careful that you make everything according to the pattern that was shown to you on the mountain.
58Heb 8:6 But Jesus has now obtained a superior ministry, and to that degree He is the mediator of a better covenant, which has been legally enacted on better promises.
58Heb 8:7 For if that first [covenant] had been faultless, no opportunity would have been sought for a second one.
58Heb 8:8 But finding fault with His people, He says: "Look, the days are coming," says the Lord, "when I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel and with the house of Judah--
58Heb 8:9 not like the covenant that I made with their fathers on the day I took them by their hand to lead them out of the land of Egypt. Because they did not continue in My covenant, I disregarded them," says the Lord.
58Heb 8:10 "But this is the covenant that I will make with the house of Israel after those days," says the Lord: "I will put My laws into their minds, and I will write them on their hearts, and I will be their God, and they will be My people.
58Heb 8:11 And each person will not teach his fellow citizen, and each his brother, saying, 'Know the Lord,' because they will all know Me, from the least to the greatest of them.
58Heb 8:12 For I will be merciful to their wrongdoing, and I will never again remember their sins."
58Heb 8:13 By saying, a new [ covenant], He has declared that the first is old. And what is old and aging is about to disappear.
58Heb 9:1 Now the first [covenant] also had regulations for ministry and an earthly sanctuary.
58Heb 9:2 For a tabernacle was set up; and in the first room, which is called "the holy place," were the lampstand, the table, and the presentation loaves.
58Heb 9:3 Behind the second curtain, the tabernacle was called "the holy of holies."
58Heb 9:4 It contained the gold altar of incense and the ark of the covenant, covered with gold on all sides, in which there was a gold jar containing the manna, Aaron's rod that budded, and the tablets of the covenant.
58Heb 9:5 The cherubim of glory were above it overshadowing the mercy seat. It is not possible to speak about these things in detail right now.
58Heb 9:6 These things having been set up this way, the priests enter the first room repeatedly, performing their ministry.
58Heb 9:7 But the high priest alone enters the second room, and that only once a year, and never without blood, which he offers for himself and for the sins of the people committed in ignorance.
58Heb 9:8 The Holy Spirit was making it clear that the way into the holy of holies had not yet been disclosed while the first tabernacle was still standing.
58Heb 9:9 This is a symbol for the present time, during which gifts and sacrifices are offered that cannot perfect the worshiper's conscience.
58Heb 9:10 They are physical regulations and only deal with food, drink, and various washings imposed until the time of restoration.
58Heb 9:11 Now the Messiah has appeared, high priest of the good things that have come. In the greater and more perfect tabernacle not made with hands (that is, not of this creation),
58Heb 9:12 He entered the holy of holies once for all, not by the blood of goats and calves, but by His own blood, having obtained eternal redemption.
58Heb 9:13 For if the blood of goats and bulls and the ashes of a heifer sprinkling those who are defiled, sanctify for the purification of the flesh,
58Heb 9:14 how much more will the blood of the Messiah, who through the eternal Spirit offered Himself without blemish to God, cleanse our consciences from dead works to serve the living God?
58Heb 9:15 Therefore He is the mediator of a new covenant, so that those who are called might receive the promise of the eternal inheritance, because a death has taken place for redemption from the transgressions [committed] under the first covenant.
58Heb 9:16 Where a will exists, the death of the testator must be established.
58Heb 9:17 For a will is valid only when people die, since it is never in force while the testator is living.
58Heb 9:18 That is why even the first covenant was inaugurated with blood.
58Heb 9:19 For when every commandment had been proclaimed by Moses to all the people according to the law, he took the blood of calves and goats, along with water, scarlet wool, and hyssop, and sprinkled the scroll itself and all the people,
58Heb 9:20 saying, This is the blood of the covenant that God has commanded for you.
58Heb 9:21 In the same way, he sprinkled the tabernacle and all the vessels of worship with blood.
58Heb 9:22 According to the law almost everything is purified with blood, and without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness.
58Heb 9:23 Therefore it was necessary for the copies of the things in the heavens to be purified with these [sacrifices], but the heavenly things themselves [to be purified] with better sacrifices than these.
58Heb 9:24 For the Messiah did not enter a sanctuary made with hands (only a model of the true one) but into heaven itself, that He might now appear in the presence of God for us.
58Heb 9:25 He did not do this to offer Himself many times, as the high priest enters the sanctuary yearly with the blood of another.
58Heb 9:26 Otherwise, He would have had to suffer many times since the foundation of the world. But now He has appeared one time, at the end of the ages, for the removal of sin by the sacrifice of Himself.
58Heb 9:27 And just as it is appointed for people to die once-- and after this, judgment--
58Heb 9:28 so also the Messiah, having been offered once to bear the sins of many, will appear a second time, not to bear sin, but to bring salvation to those who are waiting for Him.
58Heb 10:1 Since the law has [only] a shadow of the good things to come, and not the actual form of those realities, it can never perfect the worshipers by the same sacrifices they continually offer year after year.
58Heb 10:2 Otherwise, wouldn't they have stopped being offered, since the worshipers, once purified, would no longer have any consciousness of sins?
58Heb 10:3 But in the sacrifices there is a reminder of sins every year.
58Heb 10:4 For it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins.
58Heb 10:5 Therefore, as He was coming into the world, He said: You did not want sacrifice and offering, but You prepared a body for Me.
58Heb 10:6 You did not delight in whole burnt offerings and sin offerings.
58Heb 10:7 Then I said, "See, I have come-- it is written about Me in the volume of the scroll-- to do Your will, O God!"
58Heb 10:8 After He says above, You did not desire or delight in sacrifices and offerings, whole burnt offerings and sin offerings, (which are offered according to the law),
58Heb 10:9 He then says, See, I have come to do Your will. He takes away the first to establish the second.
58Heb 10:10 By this will, we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once and for all.
58Heb 10:11 Now every priest stands day after day ministering and offering time after time the same sacrifices, which can never take away sins.
58Heb 10:12 But this man, after offering one sacrifice for sins forever, sat down at the right hand of God.
58Heb 10:13 He is now waiting until His enemies are made His footstool.
58Heb 10:14 For by one offering He has perfected forever those who are sanctified.
58Heb 10:15 The Holy Spirit also testifies to us about this. For after He had said:
58Heb 10:16 This is the covenant that I will make with them after those days, says the Lord: I will put My laws on their hearts, and I will write them on their minds,
58Heb 10:17 [He adds]: I will never again remember their sins and their lawless acts.
58Heb 10:18 Now where there is forgiveness of these, there is no longer an offering for sin.
58Heb 10:19 Therefore, brothers, since we have boldness to enter the sanctuary through the blood of Jesus,
58Heb 10:20 by the new and living way that He has inaugurated for us, through the curtain (that is, His flesh);
58Heb 10:21 and since we have a great high priest over the house of God,
58Heb 10:22 let us draw near with a true heart in full assurance of faith, our hearts sprinkled [clean] from an evil conscience and our bodies washed in pure water.
58Heb 10:23 Let us hold on to the confession of our hope without wavering, for He who promised is faithful.
58Heb 10:24 And let us be concerned about one another in order to promote love and good works,
58Heb 10:25 not staying away from our meetings, as some habitually do, but encouraging each other, and all the more as you see the day drawing near.
58Heb 10:26 For if we deliberately sin after receiving the knowledge of the truth, there no longer remains a sacrifice for sins,
58Heb 10:27 but a terrifying expectation of judgment, and the fury of a fire about to consume the adversaries.
58Heb 10:28 If anyone disregards Moses' law, he dies without mercy, based on the testimony of two or three witnesses.
58Heb 10:29 How much worse punishment, do you think one will deserve who has trampled on the Son of God, regarded as profane the blood of the covenant by which he was sanctified, and insulted the Spirit of grace?
58Heb 10:30 For we know the One who has said, Vengeance belongs to Me, I will repay, and again, The Lord will judge His people.
58Heb 10:31 It is a terrifying thing to fall into the hands of the living God!
58Heb 10:32 Remember the earlier days when, after you had been enlightened, you endured a hard struggle with sufferings.
58Heb 10:33 Sometimes you were publicly exposed to taunts and afflictions, and at other times you were companions of those who were treated that way.
58Heb 10:34 For you sympathized with the prisoners and accepted with joy the confiscation of your possessions, knowing that you yourselves have a better and enduring possession.
58Heb 10:35 So don't throw away your confidence, which has a great reward.
58Heb 10:36 For you need endurance, so that after you have done God's will, you may receive what was promised.
58Heb 10:37 For in yet a very little while, the Coming One will come and not delay.
58Heb 10:38 But My righteous one will live by faith; and if he draws back, My soul has no pleasure in him.
58Heb 10:39 But we are not those who draw back and are destroyed, but those who have faith and obtain life.
58Heb 11:1 Now faith is the reality of what is hoped for, the proof of what is not seen.
58Heb 11:2 For by it our ancestors were approved.
58Heb 11:3 By faith we understand that the universe was created by the word of God, so that what is seen has been made from things that are not visible.
58Heb 11:4 By faith Abel offered to God a better sacrifice than Cain [did]. By this he was approved as a righteous man, because God approved his gifts, and even though he is dead, he still speaks through this.
58Heb 11:5 By faith, Enoch was taken away so that he did not experience death, and he was not to be found because God took him away. For prior to his transformation he was approved, having pleased God.
58Heb 11:6 Now without faith it is impossible to please God, for the one who draws near to Him must believe that He exists and rewards those who seek Him.
58Heb 11:7 By faith Noah, after being warned about what was not yet seen, in reverence built an ark to deliver his family. By this he condemned the world and became an heir of the righteousness that comes by faith.
58Heb 11:8 By faith Abraham, when he was called, obeyed and went out to a place he was going to receive as an inheritance; he went out, not knowing where he was going.
58Heb 11:9 By faith he stayed as a foreigner in the land of promise, living in tents with Isaac and Jacob, co-heirs of the same promise.
58Heb 11:10 For he was looking forward to the city that has foundations, whose architect and builder is God.
58Heb 11:11 By faith even Sarah herself, when she was barren, received power to conceive offspring, even though she was past the age, since she considered that the One who had promised was faithful.
58Heb 11:12 And therefore from one man-- in fact, from one as good as dead-- came offspring as numerous as the stars of heaven and as innumerable as the grains of sand by the seashore.
58Heb 11:13 These all died in faith without having received the promises, but they saw them from a distance, greeted them, and confessed that they were foreigners and temporary residents on the earth.
58Heb 11:14 Now those who say such things make it clear that they are seeking a homeland.
58Heb 11:15 If they had been remembering that land they came from, they would have had opportunity to return.
58Heb 11:16 But they now aspire to a better land-- a heavenly one. Therefore God is not ashamed to be called their God, for He has prepared a city for them.
58Heb 11:17 By faith Abraham, when he was tested, offered up Isaac; he who had received the promises was offering up his unique son,
58Heb 11:18 about whom it had been said, In Isaac your seed will be called.
58Heb 11:19 He considered God to be able even to raise someone from the dead, from which he also got him back as an illustration.
58Heb 11:20 By faith Isaac blessed Jacob and Esau concerning things to come.
58Heb 11:21 By faith Jacob, when he was dying, blessed each of the sons of Joseph, and, he worshiped, leaning on the top of his staff.
58Heb 11:22 By faith Joseph, as he was nearing the end of his life, mentioned the exodus of the sons of Israel and gave instructions concerning his bones.
58Heb 11:23 By faith Moses, after he was born, was hidden by his parents for three months, because they saw that the child was beautiful, and they didn't fear the king's edict.
58Heb 11:24 By faith Moses, when he had grown up, refused to be called the son of Pharaoh's daughter
58Heb 11:25 and chose to suffer with the people of God rather than to enjoy the short-lived pleasure of sin.
58Heb 11:26 For he considered reproach for the sake of the Messiah to be greater wealth than the treasures of Egypt, since his attention was on the reward.
58Heb 11:27 By faith he left Egypt behind, not being afraid of the king's anger, for he persevered, as one who sees Him who is invisible.
58Heb 11:28 By faith he instituted the Passover and the sprinkling of the blood, so that the destroyer of the firstborn might not touch them.
58Heb 11:29 By faith they crossed the Red Sea as though they were on dry land. When the Egyptians attempted to do this, they were drowned.
58Heb 11:30 By faith the walls of Jericho fell down after being encircled for seven days.
58Heb 11:31 By faith Rahab the prostitute received the spies in peace and didn't perish with those who disobeyed.
58Heb 11:32 And what more can I say? Time is too short for me to tell about Gideon, Barak, Samson, Jephthah, of David and Samuel and the prophets,
58Heb 11:33 who by faith conquered kingdoms, administered justice, obtained promises, shut the mouths of lions,
58Heb 11:34 quenched the raging of fire, escaped the edge of the sword, gained strength after being weak, became mighty in battle, and put foreign armies to flight.
58Heb 11:35 Women received their dead raised to life again. Some men were tortured, not accepting release, so that they might gain a better resurrection,
58Heb 11:36 and others experienced mockings and scourgings, as well as bonds and imprisonment.
58Heb 11:37 They were stoned, they were sawed in two, they died by the sword, they wandered about in sheepskins, in goatskins, destitute, afflicted, and mistreated.
58Heb 11:38 The world was not worthy of them. They wandered in deserts, mountains, caves, and holes in the ground.
58Heb 11:39 All these were approved through their faith, but they did not receive what was promised,
58Heb 11:40 since God had provided something better for us, so that they would not be made perfect without us.
58Heb 12:1 Therefore since we also have such a large cloud of witnesses surrounding us, let us lay aside every weight and the sin that so easily ensnares us, and run with endurance the race that lies before us,
58Heb 12:2 keeping our eyes on Jesus, the source and perfecter of our faith, who for the joy that lay before Him endured a cross and despised the shame, and has sat down at the right hand of God's throne.
58Heb 12:3 For consider Him who endured such hostility from sinners against Himself, so that you won't grow weary and lose heart.
58Heb 12:4 In struggling against sin, you have not yet resisted to the point of shedding your blood.
58Heb 12:5 And you have forgotten the exhortation that addresses you as sons: My son, do not take the Lord's discipline lightly, or faint when you are reproved by Him;
58Heb 12:6 for the Lord disciplines the one He loves, and punishes every son whom He receives.
58Heb 12:7 Endure it as discipline: God is dealing with you as sons. For what son is there whom a father does not discipline?
58Heb 12:8 But if you are without discipline-- which all receive-- then you are illegitimate children and not sons.
58Heb 12:9 Furthermore, we had natural fathers discipline us, and we respected them. Shouldn't we submit even more to the Father of spirits and live?
58Heb 12:10 For they disciplined us for a short time based on what seemed good to them, but He does it for our benefit, so that we can share His holiness.
58Heb 12:11 No discipline seems enjoyable at the time, but painful. Later on, however, it yields the fruit of peace and righteousness to those who have been trained by it.
58Heb 12:12 Therefore strengthen your tired hands and weakened knees,
58Heb 12:13 and make straight paths for your feet, so that what is lame may not be dislocated, but healed instead.
58Heb 12:14 Pursue peace with everyone, and holiness-- without it no one will see the Lord.
58Heb 12:15 See to it that no one falls short of the grace of God and that no root of bitterness springs up, causing trouble and by it, defiling many.
58Heb 12:16 And see that there isn't any immoral or irreverent person like Esau, who sold his birthright in exchange for one meal.
58Heb 12:17 For you know that later, when he wanted to inherit the blessing, he was rejected because he didn't find any opportunity for repentance, though he sought it with tears.
58Heb 12:18 For you have not come to what could be touched, to a blazing fire, to darkness, gloom, and storm,
58Heb 12:19 to the blast of a trumpet, and the sound of words. (Those who heard it begged that not another word be spoken to them,
58Heb 12:20 for they could not bear what was commanded: And if even an animal touches the mountain, it must be stoned!
58Heb 12:21 And the appearance was so terrifying that Moses said, I am terrified and trembling.)
58Heb 12:22 Instead, you have come to Mount Zion, to the city of the living God (the heavenly Jerusalem), to myriads of angels in festive gathering,
58Heb 12:23 to the assembly of the firstborn whose names have been written in heaven, to God who is the judge of all, to the spirits of righteous people made perfect,
58Heb 12:24 to Jesus (mediator of a new covenant), and to the sprinkled blood, which says better things than the [blood] of Abel.
58Heb 12:25 See that you do not reject the One who speaks; for if they did not escape when they rejected Him who warned them on earth, even less will we if we turn away from Him who warns us from heaven.
58Heb 12:26 His voice shook the earth at that time, but now He has promised, Yet once more I will shake not only the earth but also heaven.
58Heb 12:27 Now this expression, "Yet once more," indicates the removal of what can be shaken-- that is, created things-- so that what is not shaken might remain.
58Heb 12:28 Therefore, since we are receiving a kingdom that cannot be shaken, let us hold on to grace. By it, we may serve God acceptably, with reverence and awe;
58Heb 12:29 for our God is a consuming fire.
58Heb 13:1 Let brotherly love continue.
58Heb 13:2 Don't neglect to show hospitality, for by doing this some have welcomed angels as guests without knowing it.
58Heb 13:3 Remember the prisoners, as though you were in prison with them, and the mistreated, as though you yourselves were suffering bodily.
58Heb 13:4 Marriage must be respected by all, and the marriage bed kept undefiled, because God will judge immoral people and adulterers.
58Heb 13:5 Your life should be free from the love of money. Be satisfied with what you have, for He Himself has said, I will never leave you or forsake you.
58Heb 13:6 Therefore, we may boldly say: The Lord is my helper; I will not be afraid. What can man do to me?
58Heb 13:7 Remember your leaders who have spoken God's word to you. As you carefully observe the outcome of their lives, imitate their faith.
58Heb 13:8 Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today, and forever.
58Heb 13:9 Don't be led astray by various kinds of strange teachings; for it is good for the heart to be established by grace and not by foods, since those involved in them have not benefited.
58Heb 13:10 We have an altar from which those who serve the tabernacle do not have a right to eat.
58Heb 13:11 For the bodies of those animals whose blood is brought into the holy of holies by the high priest as a sin offering are burned outside the camp.
58Heb 13:12 Therefore Jesus also suffered outside the gate, so that He might sanctify the people by His own blood.
58Heb 13:13 Let us then go to Him outside the camp, bearing His disgrace.
58Heb 13:14 For here we do not have an enduring city; instead, we seek the one to come.
58Heb 13:15 Therefore, through Him let us continually offer up to God a sacrifice of praise, that is, the fruit of our lips that confess His name.
58Heb 13:16 Don't neglect to do good and to share, for God is pleased with such sacrifices.
58Heb 13:17 Obey your leaders and submit to them, for they keep watch over your souls as those who will give an account, so that they can do this with joy and not with grief, for that would be unprofitable for you.
58Heb 13:18 Pray for us; for we are convinced that we have a clear conscience, wanting to conduct ourselves honorably in everything.
58Heb 13:19 And I especially urge you to pray that I may be restored to you very soon.
58Heb 13:20 Now may the God of peace, who brought up from the dead our Lord Jesus-- the great Shepherd of the sheep-- with the blood of the everlasting covenant,
58Heb 13:21 equip you with all that is good to do His will, working in us what is pleasing in His sight, through Jesus Christ, to whom be glory forever and ever. Amen.
58Heb 13:22 Brothers, I urge you to receive this word of exhortation, for I have written to you in few words.
58Heb 13:23 Be aware that our brother Timothy has been released. If he comes soon enough, he will be with me when I see you.
58Heb 13:24 Greet all your leaders and all the saints. Those who are from Italy greet you.
58Heb 13:25 Grace be with all of you.
